        <example xml:id="example-systems-of-equations-substitution-intro">
            <title>An Example from the New York Times</title>
            <p>In 2014, the <url href="https://nyti.ms/2pupebT">New York Times</url> posted the following about the movie, <q>The Interview</q>:

                <blockquote>
                    <p><q>The Interview,</q> generated roughly <m>\$15</m> million in online sales and rentals during its first four days of availability, Sony Pictures said on Sunday.</p>

                    <p>Sony did not say how much of that total represented <m>\$6</m> digital rentals versus <m>\$15</m> sales. The studio said there were about two million transactions overall.</p>
                </blockquote>
            </p>
                
            <p>A few days later, Joey Devilla cleverly pointed out in <url href="http://www.joeydevilla.com/2014/12/31/the-new-york-times-unintentionally-provided-the-answer-to-their-question-is-algebra-necessary/">this article</url>, that there is enough information given to find the amount of sales versus rentals. Using algebra, we can write a system of equations and solve it to find the two quantities.
            </p>
            <p>First, we will define our two variables. Let <m>r</m> be the number of rental transactions (in millions) and let <m>s</m> be the number of sales transactions (in millions).</p>

            <p>The article says that the total number of transactions is 2 million, so our first equation will add the total number of rental and sales transactions to equal 2 million. Our equation is:
                <me>r+s=2</me>
            </p>

            <p>The price of each rental was <m>\$6</m>, so the number of dollars (in millions) generated from rentals was <m>6r</m>. The price of each sale was <m>\$15</m>, so the revenue (in millions) from sales was <m>15s</m>. The total revenue was <m>\$15</m> million, which we can represent with this equation:
                <me>6r+15s=15</me>
            </p>

            <p>If you are not sure about how to write an equation, use the units to help you. The units of each term in an equation must match because we can only add like quantities. The unit of measure in the first equation is transactions. The unit of measure in the second equation is dollars. Here is our system of equations:
                <me>\left\{
                    \begin{alignedat}{4}
                    r\amp{}+{}\amp s\amp{}={}\amp2 \\
                    6r\amp{}+{}\amp 15s\amp{}={}\amp15
                    \end{alignedat}
                \right.
                </me>
            To solve the system, we will use the <term>substitution method</term>. We will take an expression that is equivalent to <m>r</m> from one equation and <em>substitute</em> it into the other equation. It is easier to solve for <m>r</m> in the first equation so that is where we will begin:
                <md>
                    <mrow>r+s \amp=2 </mrow>
                    <mrow>r+s \subtractright{s} \amp=2\subtractright{s} </mrow>
                    <mrow>r \amp=2-s</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>This tells us that the expression <m>2-s</m> is equivalent to r, so we can <em>substitute</em> it for <m>r</m> in the second equation:
                <md>
                    <mrow>6r+15s \amp=15</mrow>
                    <mrow>6(\substitute{2-s})+15s \amp=15</mrow>
                </md>
            Now we have an equation with only one variable, which we will solve for <m>s</m>:
                <md>
                    <mrow>6(2-s)+15s \amp=15</mrow>
                    <mrow>12-6s+15s \amp=15</mrow>
                    <mrow>12+9s \amp= 15</mrow>
                    <mrow>12+9s\subtractright{12} \amp= 15\subtractright{12}</mrow>
                    <mrow>9s \amp= 3</mrow>
                    <mrow>\divideunder{9s}{9} \amp= \divideunder{3}{9}</mrow>
                    <mrow>s \amp= \frac{1}{3}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p>At this point, we know that <m>s=\frac{1}{3}</m>. This tells us that out of the <m>2</m> million transactions, <m>\frac{1}{3}</m> million were from online sales. We can mentally determine that this leaves <m>1\frac{2}{3}</m> million rental transactions. Algebraically, recall that we have already solved the first equation for r. To find r, we will replace <m>s</m> with <m>\frac{1}{3}</m> in that equation.
                <md>
                    <mrow>r \amp=2-s</mrow>
                    <mrow>r \amp=2-\substitute{\frac{1}{3}}</mrow>
                    <mrow>r \amp= 1\frac{2}{3}\text{ or }\frac{5}{3}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            
            <p>To check our answer, we will see if <m>s=\frac{1}{3}</m> and <m>r=\frac{5}{3}</m> make both equations true:
            <md>
                <mrow>r+s \amp=2</mrow>
                <mrow>\substitute{\frac{5}{3}}+\substitute{\frac{1}{3}} \amp\stackrel{?}{=}2</mrow>
                <mrow>\frac{6}{3} \amp\stackrel{\checkmark}{=}2</mrow>
            </md>
            <intertext>and</intertext>
            <md>
                <mrow>6r+15s \amp=15</mrow>
                <mrow>6\left(\substitute{\frac{5}{3}}\right)+15\left(\substitute{\frac{1}{3}}\right) \amp\stackrel{?}{=}15</mrow>
                <mrow>10+5 \amp\stackrel{\checkmark}{=}15</mrow>
            </md>
            </p>

            <p>In summary, the number of sales was <m>\frac{1}{3}</m> million (or <m>333{,}333</m> copies sold) and the number of rentals was <m>1\frac{2}{3}</m> million (or <m>1{,}666{,}667</m> copies rented).
            </p>
        </example>  

        <remark>
            <p>In <xref ref="example-systems-of-equations-substitution-intro">Example</xref>, we <em>chose</em> to solve the equation <m>r+s=2</m> for <m>r</m>. We could have instead solved for <m>s</m>. In that case we would have found <m>s=\frac{5}{3}</m> first, and then <m>r=\frac{1}{3}</m>.</p>
            <p>Similarly, in solving for the second variable, we used the equation that was already solved for <m>r</m>. We could have used either of the original equations to find <m>s</m>. We will look for the way with the fewest steps.</p>
        </remark>

