        <example xml:id="example-solving-system-of-equations-substitution-integers-solution">
            <statement>
                <p>Solve the system of equations using the substitution method:
                    <md>
                    <mrow>
                            \left\{
                                \begin{alignedat}{4}
                                x+2y \amp {}={} 8 \\
                                3x -2y \amp {}={} 8 \\
                                \end{alignedat}
                            \right.
                        </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>            
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>To begin, we need to solve for one of the variables in one of our equations. Looking at both equations, it will be easiest to solve for <m>x</m> in the first equation:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>x+2y\amp=8</mrow>
                        <mrow>x+2y\subtractright{2y}\amp=8\subtractright{2y}</mrow>
                        <mrow>x\amp= 8-2y</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>

                <p>Next, we will replace <m>x</m> in the second equation with <m>8-2y</m>. This will give us a linear equation in one variable that we can solve for <m>y</m>:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>3x-2y\amp=8</mrow>
                        <mrow>3(\substitute{8-2y})-2y\amp=8</mrow>
                        <mrow>24-6y-2y\amp=8</mrow>
                        <mrow>24-8y\amp=8</mrow>
                        <mrow>-8y\amp=-16</mrow>
                        <mrow>y\amp=2</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>Now that we have the value for <m>y</m>, we need to find the value for <m>x</m>. We have already solved the first equation for <m>x</m>, so that is the easiest equation to use.
                    <md>
                        <mrow>x\amp= 8-2y</mrow>
                        <mrow>x\amp= 8-2(\substitute{2})</mrow>
                        <mrow>x\amp= 8-4</mrow>
                        <mrow>x\amp=4</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>

                <p>To check this solution, we replace <m>x</m> with <m>4</m> and <m>y</m> with <m>2</m> in each equation:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>x+2y\amp=8</mrow>
                        <mrow>\substitute{4}+2\substitute{(2)}\amp\stackrel{?}{=}8</mrow>
                        <mrow>4+4\amp\stackrel{\checkmark}{=}8</mrow>
                    </md>
                    <intertext>and</intertext>
                    <md>
                        <mrow>3x-2y\amp=8</mrow>                        
                        <mrow>3\substitute{(4)}-2\substitute{(2)}\amp\stackrel{?}{=}8</mrow>                        
                        <mrow>12-4\amp\stackrel{\checkmark}{=}8</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>

                <p>We conclude then that this system of equations is true when <m>x=4</m> and <m>y=2</m>. Our solution is the point <m>(4,2)</m> and we write the solution set as <m>\{(4,2)\}</m>.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example>
            <title>Clearing Fractions Before Solving</title>
            <statement>
                <p>Solve the system of equations using the substitution method:<md>
                    <mrow>
                        \left\{
                            \begin{alignedat}{4}
                            \frac{x}{3} - \frac{1}{2}y - \frac{5}{6} \amp = 0 \\
                            \frac{1}{4}x \amp = \frac{y}{2} + 1 \\
                            \end{alignedat}
                        \right.
                    </mrow></md></p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>Before solving, we will remove the fractions in both equations. We will multiply the first equation by the least common denominator of <m>6</m>:<md>
                    <mrow>\frac{x}{3}-\frac{1}{2}y-\frac{5}{6}\amp=0</mrow>
                    <mrow>\multiplyleft{6}\frac{x}{3}-\multiplyleft{6}\frac{1}{2}y-\multiplyleft{6}\frac{5}{6}\amp=\multiplyleft{6}0</mrow>
                    <mrow>2x-3y-5\amp=0</mrow>
                </md>Next, we will multiply the second equation by the least common denominator of <m>4</m>:<md>
                    <mrow>\frac{1}{4}x\amp=\frac{y}{2}+1</mrow>
                    <mrow>\multiplyleft{4}\frac{1}{4}x\amp=\multiplyleft{4}\frac{y}{2}+\multiplyleft{4}1</mrow>
                    <mrow>x\amp=2y+4</mrow>
                </md>Now we have this system that is equivalent to the original system of equations:<md>
                    <mrow>
                        \left\{
                            \begin{alignedat}{3}
                            2x-3y-5\amp=0 \\
                            x\amp=2y+4 \\
                            \end{alignedat}
                        \right.
                </mrow></md>The second equation is already solved for <m>x</m>, so we will replace <m>x</m> in the first equation with <m>2y+4</m>, and we have:<md>
                    <mrow>2x-3y-5\amp=0</mrow>
                    <mrow>2(\substitute{2y+4})-3y-5\amp=0</mrow>
                    <mrow>4y+8-3y-5\amp=0</mrow>
                    <mrow>y+3\amp=0</mrow>
                    <mrow>y\amp=-3</mrow>
                </md>Now substituting <m>y=-3</m> into <m>x=2y+4</m>, we have:<md>
                    <mrow>x\amp=2y+4</mrow>
                    <mrow>x\amp=2(\substitute{-3})+4</mrow>
                    <mrow>x\amp=-6+4</mrow>
                    <mrow>x\amp=-2</mrow>
                </md>The solution set is <m>{(-2,-3)}</m>. Checking the solution is left as an exercise.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>
</subsection>

<subsection>
        <title>Solving Special Systems of Equations with Substitution</title>

        <p>Remember the two special cases we encountered when solving by graphing? Parallel lines and coinciding lines are special systems because the lines have the same slope. Let's see what happens when we use the substitution method on each of the special cases.</p>

        <example xml:id="example-solving-system-of-equations-substitution-no-solution">
            <title>A System with No Solution</title>
            <statement>
                <p>Solve the system of equations using the substitution method:<md>
                    <mrow>
                        \left\{
                            \begin{alignedat}{4}
                            y \amp {}={} 2x-1 \\
                            4x -2y \amp {}={} 3 \\
                            \end{alignedat}
                        \right.
                    </mrow></md></p>            
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>Since the first equation is already solved for <m>y</m>, we will substitute <m>2x-1</m> for <m>y</m> in the second equation, and we have:<md>
                    <mrow>4x-2y\amp=3</mrow>
                    <mrow>4x-2\substitute{(2x-1)}\amp=3</mrow>
                    <mrow>4x-4x+2\amp=3</mrow>
                    <mrow>2\amp=3</mrow>
                </md></p>

                <p>The variable has been eliminated, which happens when the lines have the same slope. That tells us this system represents either parallel or coinciding lines. Since <m>2=3</m> is false, there can be no solution to the system and they are parallel lines. We write the solution set as the empty set: <m>\emptyset</m>.</p>

                <p>We can verify this by changing <m>4x-2y=3</m> into slope-intercept form:<md>
                    <mrow>4x-2y\amp=3</mrow>
                    <mrow>4x-2y\subtractright{4x}\amp=3\subtractright{4x}</mrow>
                    <mrow>-2y\amp=-4x+3</mrow>
                    <mrow>\frac{-2y}{-2}\amp=\frac{-4x}{-2}+\frac{3}{-2}</mrow>
                    <mrow>y\amp=2x-\frac{3}{2}</mrow>
                </md>The system looks like:<md>
                    <mrow>
                        \left\{
                            \begin{alignedat}{4}
                            y \amp {}={} 2x \amp {}-{} \amp 1 \\
                            y \amp {}={} 2x \amp {}-{} \amp \frac{3}{2} \\
                            \end{alignedat}
                        \right.
                    </mrow></md>Now it is easier to see that the two lines have the same slope and different <m>y</m>-intercepts. They are, in fact, parallel lines, so the system has no solution.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example xml:id="example-solving-system-of-equations-substitution-infinite-solutions">
            <title>A System with Infinitely Many Solutions</title>
            <statement>
                <p>Solve the system of equations using the substitution method:<md>
                    <mrow>
                        \left\{
                            \begin{alignedat}{4}
                            y \amp {}={} 2x-1 \\
                            4x-2y \amp {}={} 2 \\
                            \end{alignedat}
                        \right.
                    </mrow></md></p>            
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>Since <m>y=2x-1</m>, we will substitute <m>2x-1</m> for <m>y</m> in the second equation and we have:<md>
                    <mrow>4x-2y\amp=2</mrow>
                    <mrow>4x-2\substitute{(2x-1)}\amp=2</mrow>
                    <mrow>4x-4x+2\amp=2</mrow>
                    <mrow>2\amp=2</mrow>
                </md></p>

                <p>The variable has been eliminated so this is a special system of equations with the same slope. Since <m>2=2</m> is true, the lines are coinciding and the system has infinitely many solutions.</p>

                <p>We can verify this by changing <m>4x-2y=2</m> into slope-intercept form:<md>
                    <mrow>4x-2y\amp=2</mrow>
                    <mrow>4x-2y\subtractright{4x}\amp=2\subtractright{4x}</mrow>
                    <mrow>-2y\amp=-4x+2</mrow>
                    <mrow>\frac{-2y}{-2}\amp=\frac{-4x}{-2}+\frac{2}{-2}</mrow>
                    <mrow>y\amp=2x-1</mrow>
                </md>The system looks like:<md>
                    <mrow>
                        \left\{
                            \begin{alignedat}{4}
                            y \amp {}={} \amp 2x-1 \\
                            y \amp {}={} \amp 2x-1 \\
                            \end{alignedat}
                        \right.
                    </mrow></md>Now it is easier to see that the two equations represent the same line. Every point on the line is a solution to the system, so the system has infinitely many solutions. The solution set is <m>\{(x,y) \mid y=2x-1\}</m>.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        
    </subsection>

    <subsection>
        <title>Setting up and Solving Applications of Systems of Equations</title>
        
        <p>In <xref ref="example-systems-of-equations-substitution-intro">Example</xref>, we set up and solved a system of equations for a real-world application. Here are some more scenarios that we can model with systems of equations.</p>

        <example xml:id="example-solving-system-of-equations-interest-application">
            <title>Accounts with Two Different Interest Rates</title>
            <statement>
                <p>Greta invested <m>\$8{,}000</m> in two accounts. Over one year, Account A earned <m>2\%</m> interest and Account B earned <m>5\%</m> interest. Greta earned a total of <m>\$220</m> in interest that year. How much money did Greta invest in each account?</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>To start, we will define two variables based on our two unknowns. Let <m>a</m> be the amount invested into account A (in dollars) and let <m>b</m> be the amount invested into account B (in dollars).</p>
                <p>To determine our equations, notice that we are given two different totals. We will use these to form our two equations. The total amount invested is <m>\$8{,}000</m> so we have:
                    <me>a+b=8000</me>
                Next, we will look at the total interest. Since account A earns interest at a rate of <m>2\%</m>, we find the amount of interest by multiplying <m>a</m> by <m>0.02</m>, which is <m>0.02a</m>. Similarly, account B earns interest at a rate of <m>5\%</m>, so we can represent the amount of interest from that account with <m>0.05b</m>. Our equation is then:
                    <me>0.02a+0.05b=220</me>
                As a system, we write:
                    <me>
                <!-- TODO: Please align a's and b's in the system -->
                        \left\{
                            \begin{alignedat}{3}
                            a+b\amp=8000 \\
                            0.02a+0.05b\amp=220 \\
                            \end{alignedat}
                        \right.
                    </me>
                </p>
                <p>To solve this system by subsitution, notice that it will be easier to solve for one of the variables in the first equation. We'll solve that equation for <m>a</m>:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>a+b\amp=8000</mrow>
                        <mrow>a+b\subtractright{b}\amp=8000\subtractright{b}</mrow>
                        <mrow>a\amp=8000-b</mrow>
                    </md>
                Now we will substitute <m>8000-b</m> for <m>a</m> in the second equation: 
                    <md>
                        <mrow>0.02a+0.05b\amp=220</mrow>
                        <mrow>0.02(\substitute{8000-b})+0.05b\amp=220</mrow>
                        <mrow>160-0.02b+0.05b\amp=220</mrow>
                        <mrow>160+0.03b\amp=220</mrow>
                        <mrow>0.03b\amp=60</mrow>
                        <mrow>\divideunder{0.03b}{0.03}\amp=\divideunder{60}{0.03}</mrow>
                        <mrow>b\amp=2000</mrow>
                    </md>
                Finally, we can determine the value of <m>a</m> by substituting <m>b=2000</m> into the equation that is solved for <m>a</m>:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>a\amp=8000-b</mrow>
                        <mrow>a\amp=8000-\substitute{2000}</mrow>
                        <mrow>a\amp=6000</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>In summary, the amount invested into account A was <m>\$6{,}000</m> and the amount invested into account B was <m>\$2{,}000</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <p>The next three examples are called <term>mixture problems</term>, because they involve mixing two quantities together to form a combination and we want to find out how much of each quantity to mix.</p>


        <example xml:id="example-solving-systems-of-equations-chemistry-solution-application">
            <title>Mixing Solutions with Two Different Concentrations</title>

            <statement>
                <p>LaVonda is a chemist and she needs <m>400</m> milliliters of a <m>6\%</m> saline solution, but she only has <m>3\%</m> saline and <m>8\%</m> saline solutions in the lab. How many milliliters of each solution should she mix together to make the concentration she needs?</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>The two unknowns are the quantities of each saline solution. Let <m>x</m> be the amount of <m>3\%</m> saline solution (in ml) and let <m>y</m> be the amount of <m>8\%</m> saline solution (in ml).</p>
                <p>For our first equation, the total amount of saline solution needed is <m>400</m> ml, so we write:
                    <me>x+y=400</me>
                </p>
                <p>The key to the second equation is that the concentration of each solution is multiplied by the number of milliliters in the solution. This gives us the amount of pure salt in each solution and in the mixture. We will multiply the percentage by the amount for each term to get our equation:
                    <me>0.03x+0.08y=0.06(400)</me>
                </p>
                <p>So our system is:
                <!-- TODO: Please align x's and y's and constants in the system -->
                    <me>
                        \left\{
                            \begin{alignedat}{3}
                            x+y\amp=400 \\
                            0.03x+0.08y\amp=0.06(400)
                            \end{alignedat}
                        \right.
                    </me>
                </p>
                <p>To solve this system, we'll solve for <m>y</m> in the first equation:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>x+y\amp=400</mrow>
                        <mrow>y\amp=400-x</mrow>
                    </md>
                Next we will replace <m>y</m> in the second equation with <m>400-x</m> and solve for <m>x</m>:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>0.03x+0.08y\amp=24</mrow>
                        <mrow>0.03x+0.08(\substitute{400-x})\amp=24</mrow>
                        <mrow>0.03x+32-0.08x\amp=24</mrow>
                        <mrow>-0.05x+32\amp=24</mrow>
                        <mrow>-0.05x\amp=-8</mrow>
                        <mrow>\divideunder{-0.05x}{-0.05}\amp=\divideunder{-8}{-0.05}</mrow>
                        <mrow>x\amp=160</mrow>
                    </md>
                As a last step, we will determine <m>y</m> by substituting the value of <m>x</m>:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>y\amp=400-x</mrow>
                        <mrow>y\amp=400-\substitute{160}</mrow>
                        <mrow>y\amp=240</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p>In summary, LaVonda needs to combine <m>160</m> ml of the <m>3\%</m> saline solution with <m>240</m> ml of the <m>8\%</m> saline solution to create <m>400</m> ml of solution with a <m>6\%</m> concentration.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <p>As a check for <xref ref="example-solving-systems-of-equations-chemistry-solution-application">Example</xref>, we will use <term>estimation</term> to see that our solution is reasonable. Since LaVonda is making a <m>6\%</m> solution, she would need to use more of the <m>8\%</m> concentration because <m>6\%</m> is closer to <m>8\%</m> than <m>3\%</m>. This agrees with our answer because we found that she needed <m>240</m> ml of the <m>8\%</m> solution and <m>160</m> ml of the <m>3\%</m> solution. This is an added check that we have found a reasonable solution.</p>

        <p>As another check, let's consider the possible concentrations that LaVonda could make with her two saline solutions. Could she make a 1% saline solution? How about a 10% solution? A mixture is an average of the two quantities so she can only make a concentration that is between the two that are available. Let's try an estimation problem in the next example.</p>

        <!-- TODO: Do we want to add any webwork problems around this concept? -->

        <example xml:id="example-estimating-mixing-coffee">
            <title>Estimating the Solution to a Coffee Bean Mixture Problem</title>
            <statement>
                <p>A coffee shop manager wants to mix two different types of coffee beans to make a blend that sells for <m>\$12.50</m> per pound. They have some coffee beans from Columbia that sell for <m>\$9.00</m> per pound and some coffee beans from Honduras that sell for <m>\$14.00</m> per pound. Without using algebra, estimate how many pounds of each type they should use to make <m>30</m> pounds of the blend.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>To estimate the solution, let's compare the three prices. Since <m>\$12.50</m> is between the prices of <m>\$9.00</m> and <m>\$14.00</m>, this mixture is possible. Now we need to estimate the amount of each type needed. The price of the blend is quite a bit closer to the higher priced coffee so we will need to use more of that type. We'll estimate 20 pounds of the <m>\$14.00</m> Honduran coffee beans and 10 pounds of the <m>\$9.00</m> Columbian coffee beans. How close is our estimate? In the next example we will write and solve a system of equations to find the exact answer.</p>
                
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example xml:id="example-solving-system-of-equations-mixing-coffee">
            <title>Solving the Coffee Bean Mixture Problem</title>
            <statement>
                <p>A coffee shop manager wants to mix two different types of coffee beans to make a blend that sells for <m>\$12.50</m> per pound. They have some coffee beans from Columbia that sell for <m>\$9.00</m> per pound and some coffee beans from Honduras that sell for <m>\$14.00</m> per pound. How many pounds of each should they mix to make <m>30</m> pounds of the blend?</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p>To set up our system of equations we will let <m>C</m> be the amount of Columbian coffee beans (in pounds) and <m>H</m> be the amount of Honduran coffee beans (in pounds).</p>
                <p>The equations in our system will come from the total number of pounds and the total cost. The equation for the number of pounds of coffee beans can be written as:
                    <me>C+H=30</me>
                To write the equation representing the cost, we will multiply the cost of each type of coffee by the number of pounds. We will do this for each term to get:
                    <me>9C+14H=12.50(30)</me>
                Now our system is:
                <!-- TODO: Please align C's and H's and constants in the system -->
                    <me>
                        \left\{
                            \begin{alignedat}{3}
                            C+H\amp=30 \\
                            9C+14H\amp=12.50(30)
                            \end{alignedat}
                        \right.
                    </me>
                </p>
                <p>To solve the system, we'll solve the first equation for <m>C</m>:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>C+H\amp=30</mrow>
                        <mrow>C\amp=30-H</mrow>
                    </md>
                Next, we'll replace <m>C</m> in the second equation with <m>30-H</m> and solve for <m>H</m>:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>9C+14H\amp=375</mrow>
                        <mrow>9(\substitute{30-H})+14H\amp=375</mrow>
                        <mrow>270-9H+14H\amp=375</mrow>
                        <mrow>270+5H\amp=375</mrow>
                        <mrow>5H\amp=105</mrow>
                        <mrow>H\amp=21</mrow>
                    </md>
                Since <m>H=21</m>, we can conclude that <m>C=9</m>. (We could solve this formally, but it is not nececessary.)
                </p>
                <p>In summary, they need to add <m>21</m> pounds of the Honduran coffee beans to <m>9</m> pounds of the Columbian coffee beans to create this blend. Our estimate in <xref ref="example-estimating-mixing-coffee">example</xref> was pretty close, so we know our answer is reasonable.</p>
            </solution>
        </example>

    </subsection>


